<font color="#FF0000">TEACHING ABOUT VIET NAM</font><br>
<tt>Wed Dec 11 18:15:19 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
I am a professor of nutrition at the University of California, Davis. I am the coordinator of the UCD-Vietnam Cooperative Agreement between our campus, the University of Ha Noi, and the Vietnamese Ministry of Agriculture. I served my country, but not in Viet Nam. I have visited Viet Nam three times during the past four years to work on nutrition-related, health-related projects. <br><br>
In January, 1997, I have been invited to teach an honors level class at UC Davis to 1st and 2nd year students that will explore a range of issues regarding Vietnam. The course is entitled: &quot;Viet Nam... The Way We Were... The Way We Are.  Speakers and readings will include a broad range of participants and perspectives, and will include geographers, historians, and social and medical scientists; physicians and nurses; veterans both for and against the war; Vietnamese-Americans, and Vietnamese. The primary seminar question is: &quot;Why Does the Viet Nam - American War Continue to Haunt Americans?&quot; Sub-themes include: American popular culture of the 1960s-1970s, examination of the Tet Offensive and the media; planning and management of the war; post-war consequences in America and in Viet Nam; medical and health related issues in Viet Nam and in America; and issues associated with diplomatic relations between our two countries. <br><br>
I ask you assistance: given the broad range of perspectives of Americans and Vietnamese, what would you most want to tell, describe, or explain to these bright 1st and 2nd year students about Viet Nam? <br><br>
Why -- in your view -- does Viet Nam continue to haunt Americans?<br><br>
My students and I thank you for your consideration.<br><br>
